{"title_page": "Kochi Tuskers Kerala", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2014}}\n{{Update|inaccurate=yes|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox cricket team\n| name             = Kochi Tuskers Kerala\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = File:Kochi Tuskers Kerala Logo.svg\n| nickname         = KTK\n| league           = [[Indian Premier League]]\n| captain          = [[Parthiv Patel]]\n| coach            = [[Geoff Lawson (cricketer)| Geoff Lawson]]\n| city             = [[Kochi]], [[Kerala]], India\n| owner            = {{unbulleted list|Kochi Cricket Pvt Ltd:<br>[[Ravindra Gaikwad]]|[[Shailendra Gaikwad]]|[[Shashi Tharoor]]|[[Mukesh Patel]]|[[Mehul Shah]]|[[Harshad Ramniklal Mehta]]|[[Rihen Harshad Mehta]]|[[Ramesh Khanna]]|[[Anand Shyam]]|[[Vivek Venugopal]]}}\n|founded          = 2010\n| ground           =[[Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Kochi]]\n| capacity         = 80,000\n| ground2          = [[Holkar Cricket Stadium]], [[Indore]]\n| capacity2       = 30,000\n| Ipl wins=\n}}\n\nThe '''Kochi Tuskers Kerala''' was a franchise [[cricket team]] that played in the [[Indian Premier League]] (IPL) representing the city of [[Kochi]], [[Kerala]]. The team was one of two new franchises added to the IPL for the [[2011 Indian Premier League|2011 season]], alongside the [[Pune Warriors India]]. The team franchise was owned by Kochi Cricket Pvt Ltd., which was a [[consortium]] of multiple companies.\n\n==Franchise history==\n\n=== Auction ===\nThe auction for expanding the initial eight franchises for the [[Indian Premier League]] was held on 22 March 2010. The cities involved in the [[auction]] were [[Pune]], [[Ahmedabad]], [[Kochi, India|Kochi]], [[Nagpur]], [[Kanpur]], [[Dharamsala, Himachal Pradesh|Dharamsala]], [[Visakhapatnam]], [[Rajkot]], [[Cuttack]], [[Vadodara]], [[Indore]] and [[Gwalior]]. Two new teams were selected out of 12 teams, which bid for 2011 IPL matches. [[Sahara Group]] made the highest bid in the auction and chose to base its team in Pune, at the cost of US$370m ({{Indian Rupee}}1702 crore).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/report-sahara-pune-warriors-ipl-contract-terminated-by-bcci-1909172 |title=Sahara Pune Warriors' IPL contract terminated by BCCI |publisher=Dnaindia.com |date=2013-10-26 |accessdate=2019-10-20}}</ref> Rendezvous Sports World made the second highest bid of US$333.2m({{Indian Rupee}}1533 crores), and elected to base its team in Kochi.<ref name=\"BBC_Sport\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/8578606.stm Pune and Kochi to join 2011 Indian Premier League, ''BBC Sport'']</ref> The two new [[Sports franchise|franchises]] were sold for a combined sum of money, which was greater than the combined purchase price of all the original eight IPL franchises.<ref name=\"TOI_IPL\">[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/ipl/news/pune-kochi-named-new-ipl-teams/iplarticleshow/5707869.cms Pune, Kochi named new IPL teams, ''Times of India'']</ref> With the Kochi team and Pune team participating in the 2011 IPL tournament, all four southern states in India had an IPL franchise ([[Royal Challengers Bangalore|RCB]] for Karnataka, KTK for Kerala, [[Chennai Super Kings|CSK]] for Tamil Nadu and [[Deccan Chargers|DC]] for Andhra Pradesh), while Maharashtra has two IPL franchises ([[Pune Warriors India|PWI]]) and ([[Mumbai Indians|MI]]).\n\nThe original shareholding pattern of KTK was:\n\n* [[Ravindra Gaikwad]], [[Shailendra Gaikwad]], [[Shashi Tharoor]] ([[Rendezvous Sports World]]) (26%)\n* [[Mukesh Patel]] ([[Parinee Developers]]) (26%)\n* [[Mehul Shah]] ([[Anchor Earth]]) (27%)\n* [[Harshad Ramniklal Mehta]], [[Rihen Harshad Mehta]], [[Ramesh Khanna]] ([[Film Waves]]) (12%)\n* [[Anand Shyam]] ([[Anand Shyam Estates and Developers Pvt Ltd]])(8%)\n* [[Vivek Venugopal]] ([[Elite Group of Companies]]) (1%)\n\nOf the 26% held by [[Rendezvous Sports World]] in whose name the title rights were vested, the Gaekwads would only get (10%) free plus (1%) paid, Sunanda Pushkar (5%) and another (10%) was reserved for the brand ambassador for the team.\n\nThe restructured shareholding pattern was:\n\n* [[Mehul Shah]] ([[Anchor Earth]]) (31.45%)\n* [[Mukesh Patel]] ([[Parinee Developers]]) (30.27%)\n* [[Harshad Ramniklal Mehta]], [[Rihen Harshad Mehta]], [[Ramesh Khanna]] ([[Film Waves]]) (13.97%)\n* [[Ravindra Gaikwad]], [[Shailendra Gaikwad]], [[Shashi Tharoor]] ([[Rendezvous Sports World]]) (10%)\n* [[Anand Shyam]] ([[Anand Shyam Estates and Developers Pvt Ltd]]) (9.31%)\n* [[Vivek Venugopal]] ([[Elite Group of Companies]]) (5%)\n\n=== Initial franchise issues ===\nThe franchise had been at the centre of many controversies since its inception. BCCI had given the franchise ultimatum to dissolve factionalism and infighting. After a series of lengthy meetings the company sent a letter to the BCCI requesting more time stating that the negotiations were in an advanced stage and they needed some more time to be sorted.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/content/current/story/482871.html The IPL Mess: Kochi asks BCCI for 10-day extension &#124; Cricket News &#124; Indian Premier League 2011 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo]</ref>\n\nThe BCCI announced that on 27 October '10 it would decide the fate of the Kochi team and the BCCI insisted that the two cases of the Kochi Tuskers Kerala and [[Chennai Super Kings]] and [[Rajasthan Royals]] which were expelled are different.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cochituskerskerala.com/ |title=Kochi's fate to be decided in Wednesday IPL Governing council meeting {{!}} India Cricket News {{!}} ESPN Cricinfo |access-date=18 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110316172441/http://www.cochituskerskerala.com/ |archive-date=16 March 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The IPL Governing council decided to give them a 30-day termination notice which meant that the franchise would have to reply to the notice within 30 days and if the IPL accepted their agreement then the franchise would no longer face the prospect of being terminated<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/content/current/story/483762.html IPL news: Kochi franchise gets termination notice but has 30 days to respond &#124; Cricket News &#124; Indian Premier League 2011 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo]</ref> The Kochi promoters submitted a letter to the BCCI officials with regard to the revised structure of agreement hammered out between them. The BCCI governing council meeting was held on 28 Nov 2010 at Nagpur to decide the fate of Kochi franchisee. BCCI president Shashank Manohar said the board needed more time to discuss the issue and to take legal opinion and that the final decision on Kochi Tuskers Kerala will be taken on the BCCI governing council meeting at Mumbai on 5 December 2010.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/content/current/story/489484.html The IPL Mess: BCCI defers decision on Kochi to 5 December &#124; Cricket News &#124; Indian Premier League 2011 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo]</ref> After much speculation it was finally announced by the BCCI that it was satisfied with the agreements signed by the franchise owners and the team would participate in the 2011 IPL Season.\n\n===Team name and home ground issues===\nKochi team management had announced \"Indi Commandos Kerala\" as the original team name in February 2011. The name and logo received much negative response from the fans worldwide.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/news/Kochi-fans-upset-with-name-Indi-Commandos/articleshow/7518632.cms Kochi fans upset with name 'Indi Commandos', ''The Times of India'']</ref> Things got worse by team management's further decision to drop \"Kerala\" from the team name and the reported move to [[Ahmedabad]] as the home ground;<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/news/IPL-4-Kochi-is-not-right-for-Kochi/iplarticleshow/7607880.cms IPL 4: Kochi is not right for Kochi, ''The Times of India'']</ref> comparatively high entertainment tax in Kerala (36%) was cited as the reason for the latter.<ref>[http://english.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentId=8871715&tabId=1&channelId=-1073865030&programId=1080132912&BV_ID=@@@ IPL in Kochi impossible without tax sops: Vivek Venugopal, ''Manorama Online'']</ref> This invoked a mass response in the social networking sites, particularly on Facebook,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/indicommandos-takes-a-beating/article1467488.ece | title='IndiCommandos' takes a beating | accessdate=10 December 2014 | date=18 February 2011 | publisher=[[The Hindu]] }}</ref> forcing the management to ultimately change the team name and logo. As a result, a voting poll was set up in the official site and the fans were provided the option the vote between either Kochi or Kerala as the first part of the name and the second part of the name from any of Titans, Tuskers, Tigers, Commandos and United.<ref>[http://sports.ndtv.com/cricket/news/item/170195-team-kochi-fans-to-vote-for-an-alternate-name Team Kochi fans to vote for an alternate name, ''NDTV Sports'']</ref> Tuskers which won this polling was selected as the team name and the full name was released as Kochi Tuskers Kerala.<ref>[http://www.hindu.com/2011/03/13/stories/2011031356581600.htm It's Kochi Tuskers Kerala!, ''The Hindu'']</ref> The decision to change the home ground also was dropped by the team management when [[Corporation of Cochin]] decided to waive off a 50% in the entertainment tax which now is 18% per game.<ref>[http://english.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentId=8879736&tabId=1&channelId=-1073865030&programId=1080132912&BV_ID=@@@ IPL: Kochi Corpn agrees to cut entertainment tax by half, ''Manorama Online'']</ref>\n\n===Termination from IPL===\nDue to a dispute among the owners, the Kochi Tuskers franchise failed to pay the 10% bank guarantee of the total franchise fee that it was supposed to pay before the season began. The BCCI claimed that it had sent several requests for payment to the franchise owners but received no response.<ref name=\"arbitration\">{{cite web|title=Kochi Tuskers seek IPL re-entry after winning arbitration|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/story/895393.html|website=[[ESPNCricinfo]]|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> On 19 September 2011, then BCCI president N. Srinivasan announced that the Kochi Tuskers Kerala IPL franchise was terminated by the BCCI because they failed to provide the bank guarantee to cover their annual fee.<ref name=\"business-standard.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/bombay-hc-rejects-kochi-tuskers-plea-against-encashing-bank-guarantee/450049/ |title=Bombay HC rejects Kochi Tuskers plea against encashing bank guarantee |publisher=Business Standard |date=22 September 2011 |accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> The franchise's plea seeking to restrain the BCCI from encashing its bank guarantee of {{INR}}1.56&nbsp;billion was rejected by a single bench of Justice SF Vajifdar.<ref name=\"business-standard.com\"/>\n\nOn 14 October 2011, the IPL Governing Council announced that there would be only nine teams participating in 2012 after the Kochi franchise was expelled from the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/cricket/news/179725-ipl-says-no-to-pak-players-nine-teams-to-play-in-2012|title=IPL says no to Pak players; Nine teams to play in 2012|date=14 October 2011|work=[[NDTV]] Sports|accessdate=7 September 2014}}</ref> The players from the Kochi Tuskers were auctioned to other franchises in [[2012 Indian Premier League|2012 IPL]] player auction. Players who attracted no bids had their salaries covered via the team's bank guarantee from the previous season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2012/content/current/story/544638.html |title=IPL 2012: Kochi players to be in 2012 auction &#124; Cricket News &#124; Indian Premier League 2012 |publisher=ESPN Cricinfo |date=10 December 2011 |accessdate=7 September 2014}}</ref> On 13 January 2012, the BCCI asked the foreign individual players who had signed a contract with Kochi Tuskers to sue Kochi Tuskers' owners, with the BCCI included as party to each case.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kochi's foreign players asked to sue owners|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2012/content/story/549234.html|website=ESPNCricinfo|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.ipl-schedule.net/bcci-asked-foreign-kochi-ipl-players-to-sue-owners/|title=BCCI asked foreign Kochi IPL players to sue owners}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, Rendezvous Sports World announced that it would take the BCCI to court over its termination from the IPL.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kochi Tuskers Kerala|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ipl-kochi/content/team/474668.html|website=ESPNCricinfo|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> In July 2015, a court-appointed arbitrator Justice Lahoti ordered the BCCI to pay {{INRConvert|550|c}} as compensation for terminating the Kochi Tuskers franchise agreement. ''[[ESPNCricinfo]]'' reported that the franchise owners had requested the BCCI to permit the team to return to the IPL, in lieu of the compensation awarded by the arbitrator. IPL Governing Council intends to appeal the ban.<ref name=\"arbitration\"/>\n\n==Team identity==\n===Jersey colours===\nThe jersey of Kochi Tuskers Kerala 2011 was purple hazes in orange T-shirt and orange pants . The team management had explained the selection of colours \u2013 orange  for the highest run scorer and purple  for the highest wicket-taker- the colours of the caps .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/engine/match/501215.html?innings=1;view=commentary |title=18th match: Kochi Tuskers Kerala v Chennai Super Kings at Kochi, Apr 18, 2011 &#124; Cricket Commentary |publisher=ESPN Cricinfo |date= |accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Sponsors===\n[[Federal Bank]], a major Indian commercial bank in the private sector, with headquarters in [[Aluva]], Kerala, was the principal sponsor of Kochi Tuskers Kerala.<ref name=\"newindianexpress1\">{{cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/cities/kochi/article458232.ece |title=federal-bank-is-kochi-ipl%E2%80%99s-principal-sponsor |publisher=The New Indian Express |date= |accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> The tickets for KTK's home matches were sold through Federal bank branches and their website. The Ticket sales of Kochi Tuskers Kerala was officially started in a ceremony hosted at the Le Meridian Hotel Kochi, on 28 March. Soon after, the tickets become available at the team's official ticketing partner website [[Kyazoonga|kyazoonga.com]].<ref name=\"kochiservnet1\">[http://www.kochiservnet.com/news/news.php?send=102, ''Kochiservnet.com'']</ref>\n\n[[Lotto Sport Italia|Lotto]], an Italian sports goods manufacturer was the apparel sponsor for the team.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">[http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-02-16/news/28552140_1_kochi-team-rendezvous-sports-world-ipl-kochi Kochi IPL signs up Lotto as kit sponsor, ''The Economic Times'']</ref>\n\n[[V-Guard]], an electronics company and AVT, a tea brand were the associate sponsors.\n[[Elite Foods]], [[Parinee Developers]] and [[Anchor Earth]] are the other main sponsors.\n\n===Theme song===\n{{externalvideo|video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8mwYiPEVImQ Signature song of Kochi Tuskers Kerala]}} The signature song of Kochi Tuskers Kerala is composed by veteran film score composer [[Ouseppachan]]. The music video for the song was filmed by [[Priyadarshan]] and his cinematographer Thiru. The song was shot at various locales including Paravur, Cherraai, Varapuzha backwaters and the [[Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Kochi|Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium]]. It features almost all the leading players in the team as well as Malayalam movie actress [[Rima Kallingal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/article399758.ece|title=Priyadarshan to shoot theme song for Kochi IPL|date=22 February 2011|newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]]|accessdate=2 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/priyadarshan-shooting-theme-song-for-kochi-ipl-team/143964-8-66.html|title=Priyadarshan shooting theme song for Kochi IPL team|date=21 February 2011|publisher=[[IBN Live]]|accessdate=2 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kerala9.com/malayalam/v/events/rima+kallingal+at+kochi+ipl+theme+song+shoot/|title=Rima Kallingal in Kochi IPL Team theme song}}</ref>\n\n===Seasons===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"background:#fff; width:50%;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n! '''Year'''\n! '''[[Indian Premier League]]'''\n! '''[[Champions League Twenty20]]'''\n|-\n! [[2011 Indian Premier League|2011]]\n!| Group stage (8/10)\n!| DNQ\n|}\n\n* DNQ = Did Not Qualify\n\n===Result summary===\n\n====Overall====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year!! Home/Away !! Matches!! Wins!! Loss!! No Result!! Win % \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" | [[2011 Indian Premier League|2011]]\n| Home || 7 || 3 || 4 || 0 || 42.86%\n|-\n| Away || 7 || 3 || 4 || 0 || 42.86%\n|-\n! Total\n| '''14''' || '''6''' || '''8''' || '''0''' || '''42.86%'''\n|}\n\n====By opposition====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Opposition!! Span !! Mat !! Won !! Lost !! Tied !! NR !! Win %\n|-\n| [[Deccan Chargers]] || 2011 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[Delhi Daredevils]] || 2011 || 2 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 50\n|-\n| [[Kings XI Punjab]] || 2011 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[Kolkata Knight Riders]] || 2011 || 2 || 2|| 0 || 0 || 0 || 100\n|-\n| [[Mumbai Indians]] || 2011 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 100\n|-\n| [[Rajasthan Royals]] || 2011 || 2 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 50\n|-\n| [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]] || 2011 || 2 || 0 || 2 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[Pune Warriors India]] || 2011 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[Chennai Super Kings]] || 2011 || 2 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 50\n|}\n\n==Home grounds==\n{{Main article|Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Kochi}}\nThe two home grounds of the Kochi Tuskers Kerala were the [[Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Kochi|Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium]] in Kochi and [[Holkar Cricket Stadium]], [[Indore]]. Five homes matches were held at Kochi and two at [[Indore]]. The [[Greater Cochin Development Authority]] completely over-hauled the Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium to cater for hosting IPL matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/content/series/466304.html?template=fixtures |title=Fixtures, Schedule &#124; Indian Premier League 2011 |publisher=ESPN Cricinfo |date= |accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Squad ==\n* Players with international caps are listed in '''bold'''.\n* {{color box|border=darkgray|#EEE8AA|<nowiki>*</nowiki>}} denotes a player who is currently unavailable for selection.\n* {{color box|border=darkgray|#FFCCCC|<nowiki>*</nowiki>}} denotes a player who is unavailable for rest of the season.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:85%; width:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| No.\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Name\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Nat\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Birth date\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Batting style\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Bowling style\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Signed year\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Salary\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Previous team\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| {{navbar-header|Notes|Vizag Victors Roster}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\"  style=\"background:#dcdcdc; text-align:center;\"| Batsmen\n|-\n|17|| '''[[Shafali Verma]]''' || style=\"text-align:center\"|{{flagicon|IND}} || {{birth date and age|2004|1|28|df=y}} || Right-handed || Right-arm [[off break]] || style=\"text-