-\n|Assistant coach||{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Haidee Tiffen]]\n|-\n|Batting coach ||{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Lydia Greenway]]\n|-\n|Batting mentor|| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Alex Blackwell]]\n|-\n|Spin bowling coach || {{flagicon|IND}} [[Neetu David]]\n|-\n|Spin bowling mentor || {{flagicon|IND}} [[Nooshin Al Khadeer]]\n|-\n|Fast bowling coach|| {{flagicon|RSA}} [[Ashlyn Kilowan]]\n|-\n|Fast Bowling mentor||{{flagicon|IND}} [[Jhulan Goswami]]\n|-\n|Fielding coach||{{flagicon|IND}} [[Ekta Bisht]]\n|-\n|Talent Scouts||{{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Esther Lanser]], {{flagicon|IND}} [[Nidhi Buley]], {{flagicon|PAK}} [[Almas Akram]], {{flagicon|IND}} [[Amita Sharma]],  {{flagicon|IND}} [[Reema Malhotra]], {{flagicon|IND}} [[Preeti Dimri]]\n|-\n|Wicket keeping coach||{{flagicon|TRI}} [[Merissa Aguilleira]]\n|-\n|Assistant wicket keeping coach||{{flagicon|IRE}} [[Meg Kendal]]\n|-\n|Right arm throwdown specialist||{{flagicon|SCO}} [[Kari Anderson]]\n|-\n|Left arm throwdown specialist||{{flagicon|NEP}} [[Nary Thapa]]\n|-\n|Physiotherapist||{{flagicon|IND}} Tracy Fernandes\n|-\n|Assistant physiotherapist||{{flagicon|IND}} Anuja Dalvi Pandit\n|-\n|Strength and conditioning coach||{{flagicon|IND}} Benafsha Gazdar\n|-\n|Assistant trainer||{{flagicon|IND}} Chaitra Khanvilkar\n|-\n|Assistant trainer||{{flagicon|IND}} Apoorva Nadkarni\n|-\n|Analyst|| {{flagicon|IND}} Aarti Nalge\n|-\n|Nutritionist||{{flagicon|IND}} A Nirusha\n|-\n|Massage therapist||{{flagicon|IND}} Shalini Chaudary\n|-\n|Team doctor||{{flagicon|IND}} Dr. Sireesha Anne\n|-\n|Psychologist|| {{flagicon|IND}} Dr. Chaitanya Sridhar\n|-\n|Yoga instructor|| {{flagicon|IND}} Sujitha Selvaraj\n|-\n|}\n\n==Sponsorship==\nAs of 2021,[[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] to manufacture kits for the team,[[Ramoji Group|Ramoji]] became the principal sponsor.[[Raymond Group|Raymond]],[[GVK (conglomerate)|GVK]] were the associate sponsors.Other official partners included [[Aura Thai Spa]],[[Anytime Fitness]],[[Sareen Sports Industries]],[[INOX Leisure Limited|INOX]] [[Vizag]].\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:85%; width:55%;\"\n|- \n! style=\"width:15%;background:; color:;\"|Year\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Kit manufacturer\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Sponsor (main)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Sponsor (back)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Sponsor (chest)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Sponsor (sleeve)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Sponsor (cap)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Sponsor (pant)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:; color:;\"|Other sponsors\n|-\n|2021\n|[[Nike, Inc.|Nike]]\n|[[Ramoji Group|Ramoji]]\n|[[Raymond Group|Raymond]]\n|[[GVK (conglomerate)|GVK]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n==Kit manufacturers and sponsors==\n[[Federal Bank]], a major Indian commercial bank in the private sector, with headquarters in [[Aluva]], Kerala, was the principal sponsor of Kochi Tuskers Kerala.<ref name=\"newindianexpress1\"/> The tickets for KTK's home matches were sold through Federal bank branches and their website. The Ticket sales of Kochi Tuskers Kerala was officially started in a ceremony hosted at the Le Meridian Hotel Kochi, on 28 March. Soon after, the tickets become available at the team's official ticketing partner website [[Kyazoonga|kyazoonga.com]].<ref name=\"kochiservnet1\"/>\n\n[[Lotto Sport Italia|Lotto]], an Italian sports goods manufacturer was the apparel sponsor for the team.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\"/>\n\n[[V-Guard]], an electronics company and AVT, a tea brand were the associate sponsors.\n[[Elite Foods]], [[Parinee Developers]] and [[Anchor Earth]] are the other main sponsors.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|- \n! style=\"width:15%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Year\n! style=\"width:13%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Kit manufacturer\n! style=\"width:13%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Shirt sponsor (chest)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Shirt sponsor (back)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Chest Branding\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Lotto Sport Italia|Lotto]]\n|'''Anchor Toothpaste'''\n|[[Federal Bank]]\n|'''Parinee Developers'''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of controversies involving the Indian Premier League]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.kochituskerskerala.com/}}\n* [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ipl-kochi/content/team/474668.html KTK Cricinfo]\n*[http://www.facebook.com/TuskersKochi IPL Team Page]\n{{Indian Premier League}}\n\n[[Category:Kochi Tuskers Kerala|*]]\n[[Category:Indian Premier League teams]]\n[[Category:Sport in Kochi]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs in India]]\n[[Category:Cricket clubs established in 2010]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs disestablished in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 disestablishments in India]]\n[[Category:Former senior cricket clubs of India]]\n[[Category:Cricket in Kerala]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2014}}\n{{Update|inaccurate=yes|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox cricket team\n| name             = Kochi Tuskers Kerala\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = File:Kochi Tuskers Kerala Logo.svg\n| nickname         = KTK\n| league           = [[Indian Premier League]]\n| captain          = [[Parthiv Patel]]\n| coach            = [[Geoff Lawson (cricketer)| Geoff Lawson]]\n| city             = [[Kochi]], [[Kerala]], India\n| owner            = {{unbulleted list|Kochi Cricket Pvt Ltd:<br>[[Ravindra Gaikwad]]|[[Shailendra Gaikwad]]|[[Shashi Tharoor]]|[[Mukesh Patel]]|[[Mehul Shah]]|[[Harshad Ramniklal Mehta]]|[[Rihen Harshad Mehta]]|[[Ramesh Khanna]]|[[Anand Shyam]]|[[Vivek Venugopal]]}}\n|founded          = 2010\n| ground           =[[Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Kochi]]\n| capacity         = 80,000\n| ground2          = [[Holkar Cricket Stadium]], [[Indore]]\n| capacity2       = 30,000\n| Ipl wins=\n}}\n\nThe '''Kochi Tuskers Kerala''' was a franchise [[cricket team]] that played in the [[Indian Premier League]] (IPL) representing the city of [[Kochi]], [[Kerala]]. The team was one of two new franchises added to the IPL for the [[2011 Indian Premier League|2011 season]], alongside the [[Pune Warriors India]]. The team franchise was owned by Kochi Cricket Pvt Ltd., which was a [[consortium]] of multiple companies.\n\n==Franchise history==\n\n=== Auction ===\nThe auction for expanding the initial eight franchises for the [[Indian Premier League]] was held on 22 March 2010. The cities involved in the [[auction]] were [[Pune]], [[Ahmedabad]], [[Kochi, India|Kochi]], [[Nagpur]], [[Kanpur]], [[Dharamsala, Himachal Pradesh|Dharamsala]], [[Visakhapatnam]], [[Rajkot]], [[Cuttack]], [[Vadodara]], [[Indore]] and [[Gwalior]]. Two new teams were selected out of 12 teams, which bid for 2011 IPL matches. [[Sahara Group]] made the highest bid in the auction and chose to base its team in Pune, at the cost of US$370m ({{Indian Rupee}}1702 crore).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/report-sahara-pune-warriors-ipl-contract-terminated-by-bcci-1909172 |title=Sahara Pune Warriors' IPL contract terminated by BCCI |publisher=Dnaindia.com |date=2013-10-26 |accessdate=2019-10-20}}</ref> Rendezvous Sports World made the second highest bid of US$333.2m({{Indian Rupee}}1533 crores), and elected to base its team in Kochi.<ref name=\"BBC_Sport\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/8578606.stm Pune and Kochi to join 2011 Indian Premier League, ''BBC Sport'']</ref> The two new [[Sports franchise|franchises]] were sold for a combined sum of money, which was greater than the combined purchase price of all the original eight IPL franchises.<ref name=\"TOI_IPL\">[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/ipl/news/pune-kochi-named-new-ipl-teams/iplarticleshow/5707869.cms Pune, Kochi named new IPL teams, ''Times of India'']</ref> With the Kochi team and Pune team participating in the 2011 IPL tournament, all four southern states in India had an IPL franchise ([[Royal Challengers Bangalore|RCB]] for Karnataka, KTK for Kerala, [[Chennai Super Kings|CSK]] for Tamil Nadu and [[Deccan Chargers|DC]] for Andhra Pradesh), while Maharashtra has two IPL franchises ([[Pune Warriors India|PWI]]) and ([[Mumbai Indians|MI]]).\n\nThe original shareholding pattern of KTK was:\n\n* [[Ravindra Gaikwad]], [[Shailendra Gaikwad]], [[Shashi Tharoor]] ([[Rendezvous Sports World]]) (26%)\n* [[Mukesh Patel]] ([[Parinee Developers]]) (26%)\n* [[Mehul Shah]] ([[Anchor Earth]]) (27%)\n* [[Harshad Ramniklal Mehta]], [[Rihen Harshad Mehta]], [[Ramesh Khanna]] ([[Film Waves]]) (12%)\n* [[Anand Shyam]] ([[Anand Shyam Estates and Developers Pvt Ltd]])(8%)\n* [[Vivek Venugopal]] ([[Elite Group of Companies]]) (1%)\n\nOf the 26% held by [[Rendezvous Sports World]] in whose name the title rights were vested, the Gaekwads would only get (10%) free plus (1%) paid, Sunanda Pushkar (5%) and another (10%) was reserved for the brand ambassador for the team.\n\nThe restructured shareholding pattern was:\n\n* [[Mehul Shah]] ([[Anchor Earth]]) (31.45%)\n* [[Mukesh Patel]] ([[Parinee Developers]]) (30.27%)\n* [[Harshad Ramniklal Mehta]], [[Rihen Harshad Mehta]], [[Ramesh Khanna]] ([[Film Waves]]) (13.97%)\n* [[Ravindra Gaikwad]], [[Shailendra Gaikwad]], [[Shashi Tharoor]] ([[Rendezvous Sports World]]) (10%)\n* [[Anand Shyam]] ([[Anand Shyam Estates and Developers Pvt Ltd]]) (9.31%)\n* [[Vivek Venugopal]] ([[Elite Group of Companies]]) (5%)\n\n=== Initial franchise issues ===\nThe franchise had been at the centre of many controversies since its inception. BCCI had given the franchise ultimatum to dissolve factionalism and infighting. After a series of lengthy meetings the company sent a letter to the BCCI requesting more time stating that the negotiations were in an advanced stage and they needed some more time to be sorted.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/content/current/story/482871.html The IPL Mess: Kochi asks BCCI for 10-day extension &#124; Cricket News &#124; Indian Premier League 2011 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo]</ref>\n\nThe BCCI announced that on 27 October '10 it would decide the fate of the Kochi team and the BCCI insisted that the two cases of the Kochi Tuskers Kerala and [[Chennai Super Kings]] and [[Rajasthan Royals]] which were expelled are different.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cochituskerskerala.com/ |title=Kochi's fate to be decided in Wednesday IPL Governing council meeting {{!}} India Cricket News {{!}} ESPN Cricinfo |access-date=18 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110316172441/http://www.cochituskerskerala.com/ |archive-date=16 March 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The IPL Governing council decided to give them a 30-day termination notice which meant that the franchise would have to reply to the notice within 30 days and if the IPL accepted their agreement then the franchise would no longer face the prospect of being terminated<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/content/current/story/483762.html IPL news: Kochi franchise gets termination notice but has 30 days to respond &#124; Cricket News &#124; Indian Premier League 2011 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo]</ref> The Kochi promoters submitted a letter to the BCCI officials with regard to the revised structure of agreement hammered out between them. The BCCI governing council meeting was held on 28 Nov 2010 at Nagpur to decide the fate of Kochi franchisee. BCCI president Shashank Manohar said the board needed more time to discuss the issue and to take legal opinion and that the final decision on Kochi Tuskers Kerala will be taken on the BCCI governing council meeting at Mumbai on 5 December 2010.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/content/current/story/489484.html The IPL Mess: BCCI defers decision on Kochi to 5 December &#124; Cricket News &#124; Indian Premier League 2011 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo]</ref> After much speculation it was finally announced by the BCCI that it was satisfied with the agreements signed by the franchise owners and the team would participate in the 2011 IPL Season.\n\n===Team name and home ground issues===\nKochi team management had announced \"Indi Commandos Kerala\" as the original team name in February 2011. The name and logo received much negative response from the fans worldwide.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/news/Kochi-fans-upset-with-name-Indi-Commandos/articleshow/7518632.cms Kochi fans upset with name 'Indi Commandos', ''The Times of India'']</ref> Things got worse by team management's further decision to drop \"Kerala\" from the team name and the reported move to [[Ahmedabad]] as the home ground;<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/news/IPL-4-Kochi-is-not-right-for-Kochi/iplarticleshow/7607880.cms IPL 4: Kochi is not right for Kochi, ''The Times of India'']</ref> comparatively high entertainment tax in Kerala (36%) was cited as the reason for the latter.<ref>[http://english.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentId=8871715&tabId=1&channelId=-1073865030&programId=1080132912&BV_ID=@@@ IPL in Kochi impossible without tax sops: Vivek Venugopal, ''Manorama Online'']</ref> This invoked a mass response in the social networking sites, particularly on Facebook,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-karnataka/indicommandos-takes-a-beating/article1467488.ece | title='IndiCommandos' takes a beating | accessdate=10 December 2014 | date=18 February 2011 | publisher=[[The Hindu]] }}</ref> forcing the management to ultimately change the team name and logo. As a result, a voting poll was set up in the official site and the fans were provided the option the vote between either Kochi or Kerala as the first part of the name and the second part of the name from any of Titans, Tuskers, Tigers, Commandos and United.<ref>[http://sports.ndtv.com/cricket/news/item/170195-team-kochi-fans-to-vote-for-an-alternate-name Team Kochi fans to vote for an alternate name, ''NDTV Sports'']</ref> Tuskers which won this polling was selected as the team name and the full name was released as Kochi Tuskers Kerala.<ref>[http://www.hindu.com/2011/03/13/stories/2011031356581600.htm It's Kochi Tuskers Kerala!, ''The Hindu'']</ref> The decision to change the home ground also was dropped by the team management when [[Corporation of Cochin]] decided to waive off a 50% in the entertainment tax which now is 18% per game.<ref>[http://english.manoramaonline.com/cgi-bin/MMOnline.dll/portal/ep/contentView.do?contentId=8879736&tabId=1&channelId=-1073865030&programId=1080132912&BV_ID=@@@ IPL: Kochi Corpn agrees to cut entertainment tax by half, ''Manorama Online'']</ref>\n\n===Termination from IPL===\nDue to a dispute among the owners, the Kochi Tuskers franchise failed to pay the 10% bank guarantee of the total franchise fee that it was supposed to pay before the season began. The BCCI claimed that it had sent several requests for payment to the franchise owners but received no response.<ref name=\"arbitration\">{{cite web|title=Kochi Tuskers seek IPL re-entry after winning arbitration|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/story/895393.html|website=[[ESPNCricinfo]]|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> On 19 September 2011, then BCCI president N. Srinivasan announced that the Kochi Tuskers Kerala IPL franchise was terminated by the BCCI because they failed to provide the bank guarantee to cover their annual fee.<ref name=\"business-standard.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/bombay-hc-rejects-kochi-tuskers-plea-against-encashing-bank-guarantee/450049/ |title=Bombay HC rejects Kochi Tuskers plea against encashing bank guarantee |publisher=Business Standard |date=22 September 2011 |accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> The franchise's plea seeking to restrain the BCCI from encashing its bank guarantee of {{INR}}1.56&nbsp;billion was rejected by a single bench of Justice SF Vajifdar.<ref name=\"business-standard.com\"/>\n\nOn 14 October 2011, the IPL Governing Council announced that there would be only nine teams participating in 2012 after the Kochi franchise was expelled from the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/cricket/news/179725-ipl-says-no-to-pak-players-nine-teams-to-play-in-2012|title=IPL says no to Pak players; Nine teams to play in 2012|date=14 October 2011|work=[[NDTV]] Sports|accessdate=7 September 2014}}</ref> The players from the Kochi Tuskers were auctioned to other franchises in [[2012 Indian Premier League|2012 IPL]] player auction. Players who attracted no bids had their salaries covered via the team's bank guarantee from the previous season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2012/content/current/story/544638.html |title=IPL 2012: Kochi players to be in 2012 auction &#124; Cricket News &#124; Indian Premier League 2012 |publisher=ESPN Cricinfo |date=10 December 2011 |accessdate=7 September 2014}}</ref> On 13 January 2012, the BCCI asked the foreign individual players who had signed a contract with Kochi Tuskers to sue Kochi Tuskers' owners, with the BCCI included as party to each case.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kochi's foreign players asked to sue owners|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2012/content/story/549234.html|website=ESPNCricinfo|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.ipl-schedule.net/bcci-asked-foreign-kochi-ipl-players-to-sue-owners/|title=BCCI asked foreign Kochi IPL players to sue owners}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, Rendezvous Sports World announced that it would take the BCCI to court over its termination from the IPL.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kochi Tuskers Kerala|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ipl-kochi/content/team/474668.html|website=ESPNCricinfo|accessdate=17 April 2016}}</ref> In July 2015, a court-appointed arbitrator Justice Lahoti ordered the BCCI to pay {{INRConvert|550|c}} as compensation for terminating the Kochi Tuskers franchise agreement. ''[[ESPNCricinfo]]'' reported that the franchise owners had requested the BCCI to permit the team to return to the IPL, in lieu of the compensation awarded by the arbitrator. IPL Governing Council intends to appeal the ban.<ref name=\"arbitration\"/>\n\n==Team identity==\n===Jersey colours===\nThe jersey of Kochi Tuskers Kerala 2011 was purple hazes in orange T-shirt and orange pants . The team management had explained the selection of colours \u2013 orange  for the highest run scorer and purple  for the highest wicket-taker- the colours of the caps .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/engine/match/501215.html?innings=1;view=commentary |title=18th match: Kochi Tuskers Kerala v Chennai Super Kings at Kochi, Apr 18, 2011 &#124; Cricket Commentary |publisher=ESPN Cricinfo |date= |accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Sponsors===\n[[Federal Bank]], a major Indian commercial bank in the private sector, with headquarters in [[Aluva]], Kerala, was the principal sponsor of Kochi Tuskers Kerala.<ref name=\"newindianexpress1\">{{cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/cities/kochi/article458232.ece |title=federal-bank-is-kochi-ipl%E2%80%99s-principal-sponsor |publisher=The New Indian Express |date= |accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> The tickets for KTK's home matches were sold through Federal bank branches and their website. The Ticket sales of Kochi Tuskers Kerala was officially started in a ceremony hosted at the Le Meridian Hotel Kochi, on 28 March. Soon after, the tickets become available at the team's official ticketing partner website [[Kyazoonga|kyazoonga.com]].<ref name=\"kochiservnet1\">[http://www.kochiservnet.com/news/news.php?send=102, ''Kochiservnet.com'']</ref>\n\n[[Lotto Sport Italia|Lotto]], an Italian sports goods manufacturer was the apparel sponsor for the team.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">[http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2011-02-16/news/28552140_1_kochi-team-rendezvous-sports-world-ipl-kochi Kochi IPL signs up Lotto as kit sponsor, ''The Economic Times'']</ref>\n\n[[V-Guard]], an electronics company and AVT, a tea brand were the associate sponsors.\n[[Elite Foods]], [[Parinee Developers]] and [[Anchor Earth]] are the other main sponsors.\n\n===Theme song===\n{{externalvideo|video1=[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8mwYiPEVImQ Signature song of Kochi Tuskers Kerala]}} The signature song of Kochi Tuskers Kerala is composed by veteran film score composer [[Ouseppachan]]. The music video for the song was filmed by [[Priyadarshan]] and his cinematographer Thiru. The song was shot at various locales including Paravur, Cherraai, Varapuzha backwaters and the [[Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Kochi|Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium]]. It features almost all the leading players in the team as well as Malayalam movie actress [[Rima Kallingal]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/article399758.ece|title=Priyadarshan to shoot theme song for Kochi IPL|date=22 February 2011|newspaper=[[The New Indian Express]]|accessdate=2 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/priyadarshan-shooting-theme-song-for-kochi-ipl-team/143964-8-66.html|title=Priyadarshan shooting theme song for Kochi IPL team|date=21 February 2011|publisher=[[IBN Live]]|accessdate=2 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kerala9.com/malayalam/v/events/rima+kallingal+at+kochi+ipl+theme+song+shoot/|title=Rima Kallingal in Kochi IPL Team theme song}}</ref>\n\n===Seasons===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"background:#fff; width:50%;\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n! '''Year'''\n! '''[[Indian Premier League]]'''\n! '''[[Champions League Twenty20]]'''\n|-\n! [[2011 Indian Premier League|2011]]\n!| Group stage (8/10)\n!| DNQ\n|}\n\n* DNQ = Did Not Qualify\n\n===Result summary===\n\n====Overall====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year!! Home/Away !! Matches!! Wins!! Loss!! No Result!! Win % \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" | [[2011 Indian Premier League|2011]]\n| Home || 7 || 3 || 4 || 0 || 42.86%\n|-\n| Away || 7 || 3 || 4 || 0 || 42.86%\n|-\n! Total\n| '''14''' || '''6''' || '''8''' || '''0''' || '''42.86%'''\n|}\n\n====By opposition====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Opposition!! Span !! Mat !! Won !! Lost !! Tied !! NR !! Win %\n|-\n| [[Deccan Chargers]] || 2011 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[Delhi Daredevils]] || 2011 || 2 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 50\n|-\n| [[Kings XI Punjab]] || 2011 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[Kolkata Knight Riders]] || 2011 || 2 || 2|| 0 || 0 || 0 || 100\n|-\n| [[Mumbai Indians]] || 2011 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 100\n|-\n| [[Rajasthan Royals]] || 2011 || 2 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 50\n|-\n| [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]] || 2011 || 2 || 0 || 2 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[Pune Warriors India]] || 2011 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[Chennai Super Kings]] || 2011 || 2 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 50\n|}\n\n==Home grounds==\n{{Main article|Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Kochi}}\nThe two home grounds of the Kochi Tuskers Kerala were the [[Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium, Kochi|Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium]] in Kochi and [[Holkar Cricket Stadium]], [[Indore]]. Five homes matches were held at Kochi and two at [[Indore]]. The [[Greater Cochin Development Authority]] completely over-hauled the Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium to cater for hosting IPL matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2011/content/series/466304.html?template=fixtures |title=Fixtures, Schedule &#124; Indian Premier League 2011 |publisher=ESPN Cricinfo |date= |accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Kit manufacturers and sponsors==\n[[Federal Bank]], a major Indian commercial bank in the private sector, with headquarters in [[Aluva]], Kerala, was the principal sponsor of Kochi Tuskers Kerala.<ref name=\"newindianexpress1\"/> The tickets for KTK's home matches were sold through Federal bank branches and their website. The Ticket sales of Kochi Tuskers Kerala was officially started in a ceremony hosted at the Le Meridian Hotel Kochi, on 28 March. Soon after, the tickets become available at the team's official ticketing partner website [[Kyazoonga|kyazoonga.com]].<ref name=\"kochiservnet1\"/>\n\n[[Lotto Sport Italia|Lotto]], an Italian sports goods manufacturer was the apparel sponsor for the team.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\"/>\n\n[[V-Guard]], an electronics company and AVT, a tea brand were the associate sponsors.\n[[Elite Foods]], [[Parinee Developers]] and [[Anchor Earth]] are the other main sponsors.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|- \n! style=\"width:15%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Year\n! style=\"width:13%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Kit manufacturer\n! style=\"width:13%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Shirt sponsor (chest)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Shirt sponsor (back)\n! style=\"width:13%;background:orange; color:purple;\"|Chest Branding\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Lotto Sport Italia|Lotto]]\n|'''Anchor Toothpaste'''\n|[[Federal Bank]]\n|'''Parinee Developers'''\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of controversies involving the Indian Premier League]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.kochituskerskerala.com/}}\n* [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ipl-kochi/content/team/474668.html KTK Cricinfo]\n*[http://www.facebook.com/TuskersKochi IPL Team Page]\n{{Indian Premier League}}\n\n[[Category:Kochi Tuskers Kerala|*]]\n[[Category:Indian Premier League teams]]\n[[Category:Sport in Kochi]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs in India]]\n[[Category:Cricket clubs established in 2010]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs disestablished in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 disestablishments in India]]\n[[Category:Former senior cricket clubs of India]]\n[[Category:Cricket in Kerala]]\n", "name_user": "Vallabharebejnd", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 950333698 byFylindfotberserk(talk))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kochi_Tuskers_Kerala"}
{"title_page": "Pune Warriors India", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox cricket team\n|name = Pune Warriors India\n|image = [[File:Pune Warriors India IPL Logo.png|200px]]\n\n| nickname         = PWI\n| league           = [[Indian Premier League]]\n| captain          = [[Aaron Finch]]\n| coach            = [[Pravin Amre]]\n|city = [[Pune]], [[Maharashtra]], India\n|colors =Light Blue,Black\n|owner = [[Subrata Roy]]\n|founded         = {{Start date|df=yes|5 September 2010}}\n|dissolved       = 26 October 2013\n|ground = [[DY Patil Stadium]] <small>([[2011 Indian Premier League|2011]])</small><br>(Capacity: 55,000)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/ground/343050.html|title=Dr DY Patil Sports Academy | accessdate=13 April 2013 | publisher=Cricinfo.com}}</ref><br/>[[Maharashtra Cricket Association Stadium]] <small>([[2012 Indian Premier League|2012]]\u2013[[2013 Indian Premier League|2013]])</small> (Capacity : 37,406)\n\n|title1 = [[Indian Premier League|IPL]]\n|title1wins = 0\n}}\n\nThe '''Pune Warriors India''' were a franchise [[cricket team]] that represented the city of [[Pune]] in the [[Indian Premier League]] (IPL). The team was one of two IPL franchises from the Indian state of [[Maharashtra]], the other being [[Mumbai Indians]]. It was also one of the two new franchises added to the IPL for the [[2011 Indian Premier League|2011 season]], alongside the also-defunct [[Kochi Tuskers Kerala]]. The team was owned by Sahara Group Sports Limited, a group company of the Indian business conglomerate [[Sahara India Pariwar]].<ref name=\"sahara\">[http://www.punewarriorsindia.com/about-us.php Pune Warriors owner]</ref> The team's home ground was the [[Maharashtra Cricket Association Stadium]]<ref name=\"stadium\"/><ref name=\"subrata\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ipl-6.com/2013/03/subrata-roy-sahara-stadium-ipl-2013.html| title=Subrata Roy Sahara Stadium IPL 6 2013 Matches Schedule | accessdate=13 April 2013 | publisher=ipl6.com}}</ref> located in Gahunje, Pune.<ref name=\"gahunje\">[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-07/pune/31304652_1_wheelers-service-road-gahunje Gahunje stadium]</ref>\n\nOn 21 May 2013, Pune Warriors India withdrew from the IPL over financial differences with the [[Board of Control for Cricket in India]] (BCCI) stemming from the valuation of the annual franchise fee it had to pay.<ref name=\"pullout\">[http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2013/content/story/637032.html Pune Warriors pull out of IPL]</ref> Their last match, before pulling out, was on 19 May 2013 against [[Delhi Daredevils]]. The franchise was officially terminated by the BCCI five months later, on 26 October 2013.<ref name=\"goodbye pwi\">[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/ipl/news/BCCI-terminates-contract-with-Sahara-Pune-Warriors-out-of-IPL/articleshow/24769374.cms BCCI terminates contract with Sahara, Pune Warriors out of IPL]</ref>\n\nThe team was not successful in their three years in the tournament, finishing second from last in their inaugural season and in [[2013 Indian Premier League|their final season]] and last in [[2012 Indian Premier League|2012]]. Overall, the team played 46 matches, out of which they won 12 and lost 33 (1 match no-result). The all-time leading run scorer of the side was [[Robin Uthappa]]<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=117;team=4787;type=trophy PWI batting]</ref> while the all-time leading wicket-taker was [[Rahul Sharma (cricketer, born 1986)|Rahul Sharma]].<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=117;team=4787;type=trophy PWI bowling]</ref>\n\n==Franchise history==\nOn 21 March 2010, Sahara Adventure Sports Limited successfully bid \u20b919 billion (US $3.7million) for the Pune franchise, the highest bid by any company in the history of IPL.<ref>[http://www.freezonal.com/sahara-pune-warriors-squad-ipl-2011.html Sahara Pune Warriors Squad \u2013 IPL 2011]</ref> The [[Videocon|Videocon Group]], an Indian consumer appliance manufacturer, also bid for the Pune IPL Team, but were unsuccessful. Along with [[Kochi Tuskers Kerala]], the team joined the existing eight teams in the IPL for the 2011 season.\n\n===2011 season===\n{{Main|2011 Indian Premier League}}\nBeing a new team in the IPL with a fresh auction purse, the Warriors bid very aggressively in the 2011 IPL auction held on 9 January 2011. The Warriors signed a number of top international cricketers including [[Yuvraj Singh]], Robin Uthappa, [[Jesse Ryder]], [[Angelo Mathews]], [[Murali Kartik]], [[Ashish Nehra]], [[Graeme Smith]], [[Mitchell Marsh]], [[Callum Ferguson]], [[Alfonso Thomas]], [[Wayne Parnell]] and [[Jerome Taylor]].<ref name=\"auction\">[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/ipl/news/IPL-4-auction-Who-got-whom/articleshow/11141834.cms IPL Auction 2011]</ref> Also a number of uncapped Indian players who had played for various franchises before were roped in including Rahul Sharma, [[Abhishek Jhunjhunwala]], [[Mithun Manhas]], [[Mohnish Mishra]], [[Ganesh Gaikwad]], [[Manish Pandey]] and [[Kamran Khan (Indian cricketer)|Kamran Khan]]. Yuvraj was nominated the captain of the team ahead of the 2011 Indian Premier League,<ref>[http://www.vcricket.com/cricket-news/yuvraj-will-captain-pune-warriors-in-ipl-4-23179.html Yuvraj Pune captain in IPL 4] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113040730/http://www.vcricket.com/cricket-news/yuvraj-will-captain-pune-warriors-in-ipl-4-23179.html |date=13 November 2013 }}</ref> while former [[Australia national cricket team|Australian]] [[opening batsman|opener]] [[Geoff Marsh]] was appointed as the team's coach.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/india/content/story/466155.html Geoff Marsh named Pune coach]</ref> On 3 May 2011, the Pune Warriors selected former Indian captain [[Sourav Ganguly]] to play for them as a replacement for the injured Ashish Nehra.<ref>[http://indiascanner.com/saurav-ganguly-back-in-ipl-4-with-a-dramatic-entry-in-pune-warriors-47899 Ganguly will be replacing injured Nehra in IPL 4 for Sahara Pune Warriors]</ref> This marked Ganguly's comeback to the IPL. Ganguly had been discarded by his former team [[Kolkata Knight Riders]] prior to the 2011 IPL auction and was not bought by any of the teams in the auction.<ref name=\"auction\"/>\n\nThe Warriors got off to a successful start in the 2011 Indian Premier League by defeating [[Kings XI Punjab]] and Kochi Tuskers Kerala at home. Following this successful start, however, the team's performance went downhill and they only won another 2 matches that season, which were against Kings XI Punjab and [[Deccan Chargers]], both away. Their final match of the season against Delhi Daredevils away was abandoned due to rain.<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/cricket/report/ipl-2011-delhi-end-at-bottom-after-washed-out-tie/20110521.htm Delhi end at bottom after washed out tie]</ref> Pune finished 9th and second-last that season with 4 wins, 9 losses and 1 no-result in 14 matches.\n\n===First withdrawal from IPL and return===\nSahara withdrew Pune Warriors India from the IPL along with the sponsorship of the Indian cricket team just hours before the 2012 IPL auction was about to start, providing a major blow to the Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) and the IPL, which was already reeling after the disbanding of Kochi Tuskers Kerala in late 2011.<ref name=\"withdraw\">{{cite web|title=Sahara withdraws Indian cricket team sponsorship and Pune Warriors ownership|date=13 April 2013|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/top-stories/Sahara-withdraws-Indian-cricket-team-sponsorship-and-Pune-Warriors-ownership/articleshow/11751668.cms|publisher=TOI}}</ref> They also boycotted the auction held on 4 February 2012. The main reason for the withdrawal was due to a problem in the amount of franchise fee to be paid by the Pune team. Sahara insisted that it had bid a huge amount for the Pune franchise under the notion that there would be 94 matches in the 2011 IPL season. As the BCCI later reduced the number of IPL matches to 74, Sahara demanded for a reduction in the amount of franchise fee to be paid by them to maintain viable IPL proposition.<ref name=\"pune out\"/> Other reasons included disputes between Sahara and the BCCI regarding the IPL rules, such as player retention and the 4-foreign player rule and also the refusal on the part of the BCCI to allow Pune to add Yuvraj Singh's price to their auction purse so that they could buy another player as a replacement for Yuvraj. Yuvraj was set to miss the whole [[2012 Indian Premier League|2012 season]] as he was undergoing treatment for [[germ cell tumor|germ cell cancer]].<ref name=\"withdraw\"/> On 6 February 2012, [[Subrata Roy]], the chairman of Sahara India Pariwar, said that Sourav Ganguly will take a call on reconciliation.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.ipl-schedule.net/sourav-ganguly-to-take-call-on-reconciliation-subroto-roy/|title=Sourav Ganguly to take call on reconciliation: Subroto Roy}}</ref> A week later, the BCCI announced that they have allowed Yuvraj Singh's replacement for Pune Warriors India for the 2012 season, though a deadlock still persisted between the two parties on long-term sponsorship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/et-cetera/bcci-sahara-feud-unresolved-board-refuses-to-make-any-exceptions/articleshow/11872185.cms |title=BCCI-Sahara feud unresolved, Board refuses to make any exceptions \u2013 Economic Times |newspaper=The Economic Times |date=13 February 2012 |publisher=Economictimes.indiatimes.com |accessdate=12 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 February 2012, the BCCI and Sahara ended their differences and announced that Pune Warriors India will play in IPL 5.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pune Warriors India to play in IPL 5|date=4 February 2012|url=http://www.ipl-schedule.net/pune-warriors-india-to-play-in-ipl-5/}}</ref> The BCCI agreed to give Sahara a total purse of $3.4 million, $1.6 million from the money that they had for the auction and $1.8 million as compensation due to the absence of Yuvraj. It was also decided that Pune could replace Yuvraj with one player, whose fees would be up to $1.8 million. IPL's trading window was extended up to 29 February 2012 to allow the team to purchase players. Pune was also allowed the compensation of playing 5 foreign players in the squad, subject to the consent of the other 8 franchises. The BCCI also allowed Sahara to have a strategic partner in the franchise. Pune's new stadium would be allowed to host one of the play-off matches, provided [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]] gave consent, because according to a BCCI rule, the right to host the play-off matches is given to the finalist of the previous edition. (RCB were the runners-up in the previous tournament).<ref>{{cite news|title=Sahara stays sponsor, Pune will play IPL|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref> BCCI agreed to negotiate with Sahara regarding the amount of franchise fee to be paid and also agreed to start arbitration proceedings for the same.<ref name=\"pune out\"/>\n\n===2012 season===\n[[File:PWI VS DD.jpg|thumb|right|Pune Warriors India in action against [[Delhi Daredevils]] at the [[Subrata Roy Sahara Stadium]]]]\n{{Main|2012 Indian Premier League}}\nThough Pune boycotted the IPL auction, they signed international cricketers outside the auction including [[Marlon Samuels]], [[Luke Wright]], [[Steve Smith (cricketer)|Steve Smith]], [[Tamim Iqbal]], [[James Hopes]] and [[Michael Clarke (cricketer)|Michael Clarke]]. They also signed Indian players including [[Raiphi Gomez]], [[Ali Murtaza]], [[Ashok Dinda]], [[Anustup Majumdar]] and [[Mahesh Rawat]]. Due to Yuvraj's unavailability for the entire season, Ganguly was made the captain of the franchise.<ref name=\"dada\">{{cite web|title=Sourav Ganguly's days as Pune captain over, to serve as mentor only|date=13 April 2013|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-05-10/news/31655144_1_sourav-ganguly-pune-warriors-bat-or-ball|publisher=TOI}}</ref> He was also made part of the coaching staff as a mentor.<ref name=\"mentor\">[http://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/48689/ Ganguly, Donald part of Pune coaching staff]</ref> Former South African fast bowler [[Allan Donald]] and former Indian batsman [[Praveen Amre]] were also roped in as bowling and batting coaches respectively, replacing Marsh who had resigned to become the Sri Lankan coach.<ref name=\"mentor\"/>\n\nThe team started off their IPL 2012 campaign with wins against Mumbai Indians and Kings XI Punjab away and at home respectively. But just like in 2011, the team could not maintain the initial momentum and again won only two more matches that season, against defending champions [[Chennai Super Kings]] at home and Delhi Daredevils away. Midway through the season, Ganguly was sacked as captain and was dropped from the team due to lack of results, but was retained as mentor.<ref name=\"dada\"/> However, this decision was later reversed and he returned to the team as captain. For the home match against Royal Challengers Bangalore, Ganguly rested himself, with Steve Smith taking up the captaincy, but still, the team lost by 35 runs. Pune finished last that season with 4 wins and 12 losses in 16 matches.\n\n===2013 season===\n{{Main|2013 Indian Premier League}}\nFor the 2013 season, Pune Warriors India retained Steve Smith, Tamim Iqbal, Marlon Samuels and Luke Wright but released Clarke, James Hopes, Callum Ferguson, Alfonso Thomas, Murali Kartik and Jesse Ryder. Ganguly announced his retirement from all forms of cricket in October 2012,<ref name=\"bye dada\">[http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/1757445/report-sourav-ganguly-quits-ipl-retires-from-all-forms-of-cricket Ganguly retires]</ref> leaving the franchise without a captain. In the auction which was held on 3 February 2013, Clarke was bought back by the franchise for $400,000.<ref name=\"mc\">[http://zeenews.india.com/sports/cricket/indian-premier-league-2013/clarke-could-be-paid-more-to-lead-pune-warriors-in-ipl-report_758541.html Clarke could be paid more to lead Pune Warriors in IPL: Report]</ref> The team also bought international players like [[Ajantha Mendis]] and [[Kane Richardson]] and signed domestic players like [[Abhishek Nayar]], [[Tirumalasetti Suman]], [[Ishwar Pandey]], [[Parvez Rasool]] and [[Udit Birla]] for the 2013 season. The franchise also swapped a player with the Delhi Daredevils, trading Nehra for [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]] batsman [[Ross Taylor]].<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2013/content/story/604641.html Delhi swap Taylor for Pune's Nehra]</ref> Yuvraj also returned to the team following his recovery from cancer. Unfortunately for the franchise, Clarke, who was the frontrunner to lead the team, was ruled out of the entire season with a recurring back and hamstring injury, which was aggravated during the [[Australian cricket team in India in 2012\u201313|Australian tour of India]] held earlier.<ref>[http://sports.ndtv.com/indian-premier-league-2013/news/205416-michael-clarke-out-for-10-weeks-pune-warriors-have-to-hunt-for-new-captain Michael Clarke ruled out of IPL 6, Pune Warriors have to hunt for new captain]</ref> On 28 March 2013, the franchise named Sri Lankan Test and ODI captain and all-rounder Angelo Mathews as the captain for the 2013 season<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/indian-premier-league-2013/content/story/627151.html Angelo Mathews named Pune Warriors' captain]</ref> and also signed Australian batsman [[Aaron Finch]] as a replacement for Clarke.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/ipl-pune/content/story/627230.html Finch to replace Clarke for Pune Warriors]</ref>\n\nThe team's performance in the 2013 season was pathetic and mirrored its performance in 2012 with 4 wins and 12 losses in 16 matches, finishing 8th and second-last in the league. The only matches the team won were against [[Rajasthan Royals]] (home), Chennai Super Kings (away), Kolkata Knight Riders (away) and Delhi Daredevils (home). The Warriors were thoroughly humiliated in their away match against Royal Challengers Bangalore, courtesy [[Chris Gayle]]'s 175 not out off only 66 balls and later became the first team in the 2013 season to be knocked out of contention for the playoffs after a loss to Chennai Super Kings at home. Like the previous seasons, the main cause for the team's poor performance was their constant squandering of winning chances and the lack of balance in the side, with more than 30 players being used during the season. The team was the only IPL franchise to use three captains that season. Mathews was sacked as captain following a poor start by the Warriors in the tournament and his own poor form and was replaced by Taylor for the away match against Chennai Super Kings. Following this match, Taylor was also sacked as captain due to his poor form, in spite of the team winning in Chennai, and was replaced by Finch, who captained the Warriors for the rest of the season.\n\n===Second and final withdrawal from IPL===\nOn 21 May 2013, just two days after finishing its league campaign, Sahara withdrew Pune Warriors India from the IPL for the second time in three years.<ref name=\"pullout\"/> The reason, according to BCCI, was the encashing of the team's bank guarantee after Sahara defaulted on paying the entire franchise fee.<ref name=\"pullout\"/> BCCI sources said that Sahara paid 20% of the franchise fee in January 2013 and had promised to pay the remaining amount by 19 May 2013 but they failed to do so.<ref name=\"pune gone\">[http://sports.ndtv.com/indian-premier-league-2013/news/208101-ipl-6-bcci-encashes-bank-guarantee-after-pune-warriors-fail-to-pay-franchisee-fee BCCI encashes bank guarantee after Pune Warriors fail to pay franchisee fee]</ref> But Sahara blamed BCCI for the decision to pull out the Pune franchise from the IPL. In a statement from Sahara after pulling out Pune Warriors India from the IPL, it stated that Sahara had to pull out of IPL due to the BCCI's stubborn and disinterested attitude towards the reduction of the Pune team's franchise fee.<ref name=\"pune out\"/> It also stated that Sahara was \"disgusted\" by the unsporting and biased attitude of the BCCI towards it and the Pune franchise despite its supporting of Indian cricket for more than a decade,<ref name=\"pune out\">[http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/637036.html Full text of Pune Warriors' statement]</ref> the decision to withdraw from the IPL was final and it will not return to the IPL even if the entire franchise fee is waived by the BCCI.<ref name=\"pune out\"/> However, it added that Sahara would remain the sponsor of the [[India national cricket team|Indian cricket team]] until December 2013, when its contract with the BCCI expires, following which it asked the BCCI to find a new sponsor for the team.<ref name=\"pune out\"/> Speaking to the media on 24 May 2013, Subrata Roy said that the attitude of BCCI president and [[India Cements]] chairman [[N. Srinivasan]] towards Sahara and the Pune franchise was the main reason for the withdrawal of Sahara from IPL and Indian cricket and also added that Sahara would never be associated with Indian cricket as long as Srinivasan is at the helm of BCCI affairs.<ref>[http://www.financialexpress.com/news/sack-n-srinivasan-or-wont-sponsor-team-india-subrata-roy/1120155 Sack N Srinivasan or won't sponsor Team India: Subrata Roy]</ref>\n\nOn 26 October 2013, the BCCI officially terminated its agreement with the team, bringing an end to the team's IPL sojourn.<ref name=\"goodbye pwi\"/>\n\n==Home ground==\n\n[[File:DY Patil Stadium.jpg|thumb|left|[[DY Patil Stadium]], the initial \"home\" ground of Pune Warriors India]]\n[[File:Sahara Stadium Pune 4.jpg|thumb|right|[[Maharashtra Cricket Association Stadium]] at Gahunje, the home ground of Pune Warriors India from 2012\u20132013]]\nIn their inaugural season in 2011, the team played their home matches at the [[DY Patil Stadium]] at [[Navi Mumbai]], as their designated home venue, the [[Maharashtra Cricket Association Stadium]], was still under construction. Only from the 2012 season onwards did the team actually begin to play their home matches in Pune at the Subrata Roy Sahara Stadium, named after the Chairman of Sahara India Pariwar. It is located at Gahunje, a village located about {{convert|23|km}} north-west of Pune on the [[Mumbai Pune Expressway]].<ref name=\"gahunje\"/> It has a seating capacity of 55,000 spectators.<ref name=\"stadium\">[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/ipl/venues/Subrata-Roy-Sahara-Stadium-Pune/iplvenueshow.cms Maharashtra Cricket Association Stadium, Pune]</ref>\n\nThe stadium became a source of contention between Sahara India Pariwar and the [[Maharashtra Cricket Association]] (MCA). In early 2013, Sahara moved court over the termination of the agreement between it and the MCA over the stadium by the latter. MCA had terminated the agreement on the ground due to Sahara defaulting over payments to the MCA and had renamed the stadium as the MCA Pune International Cricket Centre.<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-01-08/top-stories/36216126_1_subrata-roy-sahara-stadium-mca-interim-relief Sahara moves court against MCA over stadium in Pune]</ref> Sahara decided to play all their home matches outside Pune till the issue was resolved.<ref name=\"stad\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thatscricket.com/news/2013/03/10/pune-warriors-play-home-games-at-mha-stadium-ipl-6-066409.html |title=Pune Warriors to play home games at MCA Stadium |publisher=That's Cricket |date=10 March 2013 |accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> On 15 March 2013, the issue was finally resolved, with Sahara agreeing to pay all existing dues within three months.<ref name=\"resolve\">[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-03-16/news/37766988_1_subrata-roy-sahara-stadium-sahara-chairman-sahara-group Sahara-Maharashtra Cricket Association row settled]</ref> The stadium was renamed back to Subrata Roy Sahara Stadium and MCA also allowed Pune Warriors India to play all its home matches in the stadium.<ref name=\"stad\"/><ref name=\"resolve\"/>\n\n==Team identity==\n\n===Team name and logo===\n\nThe Pune franchise named the team Pune Warriors India in honour of the [[Maratha Empire]] which once ruled from the city. The Pune Warriors India logo was a spear wielding, attacking cavalry-warrior (warrior on horse) in the hue of the [[Indian flag|Indian tricolour]].<ref>[http://sahara.in/2010/press04.html Sahara unveiled the name and logo of its Pune IPL franchise in a glittering ceremony]</ref> The team logo is still same in.\n\n===Jersey colours===\nIn their inaugural season, the team's jersey was black with tricolor stripes and silver accents on the either sides. The jersey also incorporated the attacking warrior logo in the top-left corner of the shirt. From the 2012 season onwards, the primary colour of the jersey was changed to [[Turquoise (color)#Turquoise Blue|turquoise blue]]. [[Adidas]] was the kit manufacturer for the first two seasons, but for the third season, T. K. Sportswear was the kit manufacturer. Indian online fashion clothing brand American Swan was the official lifestyle clothing partner for the team.<ref>[http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/american-swan-is-pune-warriors-clothing-partner/article4653534.ece American Swan is Pune Warriors clothing partner]</ref>\n\n===Sponsors===\nFor their first two seasons, the main sponsor for the team was [[TVS Motors]].<ref>[http://www.telegraphindia.com/external/display.jsp?mode=details&id=26486 Creatigies makes Pune Warriors India Vroom on TVS]</ref> TVS was replaced as the team's main sponsor for their final season by [[Sansui Electric]], a Japanese consumer appliance manufacturer.<ref>[http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-04-08/news/38374174_1_pune-warriors-team-ipl-team-principal-sponsor Sansui becomes principal sponsor of Pune Warriors India]</ref> The other sponsors were [[Lux Cozi]], [[Nissan]], [[UB Group]], Linc Pens, [[Oakley Inc.]], [[YOU Broadband]], Killer Jeans and [[Finolex Group]]. For the 3 seasons of Exide BMW is the main sponsor. BMW will be replaced by Brittania as the main sponsor. The other sponsors are [[Indigo Airlines]], [[Seagrams]], [[Jockey International|Jockey]], [[Newell Rubbermaid|Reynolds]], [[Raymond Group]], [[Titan Company|Fastrack]], [[Airtel]] and Ashirwad Pipes.\n\n===Theme song===\n\nThe team's official theme song was \"Sahara Saharaa\", a [[Hindi]] song sung by leading playback singer and music composer [[Shankar Mahadevan]]. The video of the song showed a warrior riding on a horse and inspiring the Pune residents to come to the stadium where they witnessed the team cricketers. Then the team cricketers as well as the residents performed the Sahara salute (putting the right hand over the heart and saying \"Jai Sahara\").\n\n===Indian cheerleaders===\nPune Warriors India was the only IPL franchise which used Indian [[cheerleading|cheerleaders]] unlike the other franchises which use foreign cheerleaders. Known as ''Cheer Queens'', these cheerleaders were dressed up in traditional Indian attire designed by famous [[Bollywood]] designer [[Neeta Lulla]] and performed traditional Indian dances choreographed by ace choreographers [[Ganesh Hegde]] and [[Tanusree Shankar]], not the traditional gymnastic routines which are usually associated with cheerleading.<ref name=\"cheerleaders\">[http://www.infrawindow.com/weekends/ipl-cheerleaders_10_13/ IPL cheerleaders]</ref> In the words of Subrata Roy-\n\n{{quote|With Pune Warriors India's ''Cheer Queens'', we intend to showcase and bring recognition to the rich and diverse culture of India at an international platform. The opportunity, which we want all the franchisees of IPL to avail collectively, so that the rich cultural heritage of India is presented in an innovative way to the world.<ref name=\"cheerleaders\"/>}}\n\n== Squad ==\n* Players with international caps are listed in '''bold'''.\n* {{color box|border=darkgray|#EEE8AA|<nowiki>*</nowiki>}} denotes a player who is currently unavailable for selection.\n* {{color box|border=darkgray|#FFCCCC|<nowiki>*</nowiki>}} denotes a player who is unavailable for rest of the season.\n \n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"font-size:85%; width:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| No.\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Name\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Nat\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Birth date\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Batting style\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Bowling style\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Signed year\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Salary\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| Previous team\n! style=\"background:; color:; text-align:center;\"| {{navbar-header|Notes|Vizag Victors Roster}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\"  style=\"background:#dcdcdc; text-align:center;\"| Batsmen\n|-\n|77|| '''[[Shubman Gill]]''' || style=\"text-align:center\"|{{flagicon|IND}} || {{birth date and age|1999|9|8|df=y}} || Right-handed || Right-arm [[off break]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2021 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| || [[Kolkata Knight Riders]] ||\n|-\n|28|| '''[[Avishka Fernando]]''' || style=\"text-align:center\"|{{flagicon|SRI}} || {{birth date and age|1998|4|5|df=y}} || Right-handed || Right-arm [[medium-fast]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2021 || style=\"text-align:right;\"| |||| Overseas\n|-\n|97|| [[Sarfaraz Khan (cricketer)|Sarfaraz Khan]] || style=\"text-align:center\"|{{flagicon|IND}} || {{birth date and age|1997|10|22|df=y}} || Right-handed || Right-arm [[off break]] || style=\"text-align:center;\"