094-2019-08-12|title=Block TamilRockers and piracy websites: Delhi High Court to Internet Service Providers|last=DelhiAugust 12|first=Press Trust of India New|last2=August 12|first2=2019UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2019-08-30|last3=Ist|first3=2019 18:47}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/delhi-hc-directs-internet-service-providers-to-block-tamilrockers-for-unauthorised-movie-screening-2268223.html|title=Delhi HC Directs Internet Service Providers to Block Tamilrockers for Unauthorised Movie Screening|website=News18|access-date=2019-08-30}}</ref> The website continues operation by switching to a series of new web addresses.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.oneindia.com/india/2-0-leaked-why-is-it-so-hard-to-stop-the-tamilrockers-2816221.html |title=2.0 leaked: Why is it so hard to stop the Tamilrockers? |date=1 December 2018 |website=[[Oneindia]] |access-date=18 February 2019}}</ref> Aside from its traditional list of pirate sites, apps, and hosting providers, the movie industry group [[MPAA]] now lists Tamil Rockers as one of the [[notorious markets]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/mpa-adds-1xbet-and-baidu-to-latest-piracy-threat-report/|title=MPA Adds 1XBET and Baidu to Latest Piracy Threat Report|date=2019-10-13|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-10-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/images/Motion_Picture_Association_2019_Notorious_Markets_OCR.pdf|title=MPA\u2019s full report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nTamil Rockers is the tenth most popular torrent site in [[TorrentFreak]]'s Top 10 Most Popular Torrent Sites of 2020 list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/top-10-most-popular-torrent-sites-of-2020-200105/|title=Top 10 Most Popular Torrent Sites of 2020|date=2020-01-05|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nTamil Rockers was a [[bootleg recording]] network which was founded in 2011 and later became a public torrent website that links to pirated copies of Indian films in addition to Hollywood movies dubbed into regional languages along with the original English audio.\n\nOn 14 March 2018, three men said to be behind the site were arrested. One of the men was believed to be the site administrator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/kerala-police-arrest-5-piracy-3-tamilrockers-and-2-dvd-rockers-78008|website=www.thenewsminute.com|access-date=2019-08-30|title=Kerala police arrest 5 for piracy: 3 from Tamilrockers and 2 from DVD rockers|date=15 March 2018}}</ref> On 23 May 2019, more members of Tamilrockers were arrested in [[Coimbatore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/news/Members-of-piracy-website-TamilRockers-arrested/articleshow/55887838.cms|title=TamilRockers: Members of piracy website Tamil Rockers arrested - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-08-30}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:BitTorrent websites]]\n[[Category:Notorious markets]]\n", "name_user": "Sukhraj Gill", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReferences)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tamil_Rockers"}
{"title_page": "Serum (blood)", "text_new": "{{Short description|Component of blood which does not contain cells or clotting factors}}\n[[File:US Navy 030923-N-1577S-003 Hospital Corpsman 2nd Class Donna Sanderson from Lancaster, Calif., prepares serum cups.jpg|thumb|right|Preparation of serum cups for a lipids panel designed to test cholesterol levels in a patient's blood]]\nBlood '''Serum''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|\u026a\u0259r|\u0259|m}}) is the fluid and solute component of [[blood]] which does not play a role in [[Coagulation|clotting]].<ref>{{cite web|title=serum |url=https://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/serum |work=The Free Dictionary |access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref> It may be defined as [[blood plasma]] without [[fibrinogen]]s. Serum includes all [[protein]]s not used in [[Coagulation|blood clotting]]; all [[electrolyte]]s, [[antibodies]], [[antigen]]s, [[hormone]]s; and any [[exogenous]] substances (e.g., [[drug]]s or [[microorganism]]s). Serum does not contain white blood cells ([[leukocyte]]s), red blood cells ([[erythrocyte]]s), [[platelet]]s, or [[clotting factor]]s.\n\nThe study of serum is [[serology]]. Serum is used in numerous [[diagnostic tests]] as well as [[blood typing]]. Measuring the concentration of various molecules can be useful for many applications, such as determining the [[therapeutic index]] of a [[drug candidate]] in a [[clinical trial]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Kaplan |first=Larry |url=http://www.columbia.edu/itc/hs/medical/selective/AdvClinicalPathology/2005/lecture/SerumToxicologyLectureColor_Kaplan.pdf |date=2005-10-06 |title=Serum Toxicology |website=Clinical Pathology/Laboratory Medicine 2005 |publisher=Columbia University |access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref>\n\nTo obtain serum, a [[blood]] sample is allowed to clot ([[coagulation]]). The sample is then [[centrifuge]]d to remove the clot and blood cells, and the resulting liquid [[wikt:supernatant|supernatant]] is serum.<ref name=\"pmid1381403\">{{cite journal |author=Thavasu PW, Longhurst S, Joel SP, Slevin ML, Balkwill FR|title=Measuring cytokine levels in blood. Importance of anticoagulants, processing, and storage conditions. |journal=J Immunol Methods |year=1992 |volume=153 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=115\u201324 |pmid=1381403 |doi=10.1016/0022-1759(92)90313-i }}</ref>\n\nSerum is an essential factor for the self-renewal of [[embryonic stem cells]] in combination with the cytokine [[leukemia inhibitory factor]].{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Clinical and laboratory uses ==\nThe serum of [[convalescence|convalescent]] patients successfully recovering (or already recovered) from an [[infectious disease]] can be used as a [[biopharmaceutical]] in the treatment of other people with that disease, because the [[antibody|antibodies]] generated by the successful recovery are potent fighters of the [[pathogen]]. Such ''convalescent serum'' ([[antiserum]]) is a form of [[immunotherapy]].\n\nSerum is also used in [[Gel electrophoresis of proteins|protein electrophoresis]], due to the lack of [[fibrinogen]] which can cause false results. \n\n==Purification strategies==\nBlood serum and plasma are some of the largest sources of [[biomarker]]s, whether for diagnostics or therapeutics. Its vast dynamic range, further complicated by the presence of lipids, salts, and post-translational modifications, as well multiple mechanisms of degradation, presents challenges in analytical reproducibility, sensitivity, resolution, and potential efficacy. For analysis of biomarkers in blood serum samples, it is possible to do a pre-separation by [[free-flow electrophoresis]] that usually consists of a depletion of serum [[albumin]] protein.<ref name=\"Analysis of human plasma proteins: a focus on sample collection and separation using free-flow electrophoresis.\">Nissum M., Foucher AL.: ''Analysis of human plasma proteins: a focus on sample collection and separation using free-flow electrophoresis.'' In: ''Expert Rev Proteomics.'' Nr. 5, 2008, S. 571\u201387.</ref> This method enables greater penetration of the proteome via separation of a wide variety of charged or chargeable analytes, ranging from small molecules to cells.\n\n==Usage note==\nLike many other [[mass noun]]s, the word ''serum'' can be pluralized when used in certain [[word sense|senses]]. To speak of multiple serum specimens from multiple people (each with a unique population of antibodies), physicians sometimes speak of '''sera''' (the Latin plural, as opposed to ''serums'').\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Antiserum]]\n* [[Albumin]]\n* [[Blood fractionation]]\n* [[Globulin]]\n* [[Human serum albumin]]\n* [[Lipid]]\n* [[Serum iron]]\n* [[Serum protein electrophoresis]]\n* [[Serum-separating tube]]\n* [[Serum total protein]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |title=Concise Medical Dictionary |editor=Martin, Elizabeth A.|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location=[[Oxford, England]]|year=2007 |edition=7th|isbn=978-0-19-280697-0 |url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/views/ENTRY.html?subview=Main&entry=t60.e9203 |accessdate=8 September 2009}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia|author1=Wang, Wendy |author2=Srivastava, Sudhir |title=Serological Markers | encyclopedia=[[Encyclopedia of Public Health]]|editor=[[Lester Breslow]]|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers (United States)|Macmillan Reference USA]]|location=[[New York, New York]] |year=2002 |volume=4 |pages=1088\u20131090 }}\n{{refend}}\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary|serum|blood serum}}\n* [http://users.rcn.com/jkimball.ma.ultranet/BiologyPages/B/Blood.html Blood]\n\n{{blood tests}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Serology|*]]\n[[Category:Blood]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Component of blood which does not contain cells or clotting factors}}\n{{lead rewrite|date=December 2018|reason=Lead talks more about what the subject <em>isn't</em> than what it actually <em>is</em>}}\n[[File:US Navy 030923-N-1577S-003 Hospital Corpsman 2nd Class Donna Sanderson from Lancaster, Calif., prepares serum cups.jpg|thumb|right|Preparation of serum cups for a lipids panel designed to test cholesterol levels in a patient's blood]]\n'''Serum''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|\u026a\u0259r|\u0259|m}}) is the fluid and solute component of [[blood]] which does not play a role in [[Coagulation|clotting]].<ref>{{cite web|title=serum |url=https://medical-dictionary.thefreedictionary.com/serum |work=The Free Dictionary |access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref> It may be defined as [[blood plasma]] without [[fibrinogen]]s. Serum includes all [[protein]]s not used in [[Coagulation|blood clotting]]; all [[electrolyte]]s, [[antibodies]], [[antigen]]s, [[hormone]]s; and any [[exogenous]] substances (e.g., [[drug]]s or [[microorganism]]s). Serum does not contain white blood cells ([[leukocyte]]s), red blood cells ([[erythrocyte]]s), [[platelet]]s, or [[clotting factor]]s.\n\nThe study of serum is [[serology]]. Serum is used in numerous [[diagnostic tests]] as well as [[blood typing]]. Measuring the concentration of various molecules can be useful for many applications, such as determining the [[therapeutic index]] of a [[drug candidate]] in a [[clinical trial]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Kaplan |first=Larry |url=http://www.columbia.edu/itc/hs/medical/selective/AdvClinicalPathology/2005/lecture/SerumToxicologyLectureColor_Kaplan.pdf |date=2005-10-06 |title=Serum Toxicology |website=Clinical Pathology/Laboratory Medicine 2005 |publisher=Columbia University |access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref>\n\nTo obtain serum, a [[blood]] sample is allowed to clot ([[coagulation]]). The sample is then [[centrifuge]]d to remove the clot and blood cells, and the resulting liquid [[wikt:supernatant|supernatant]] is serum.<ref name=\"pmid1381403\">{{cite journal |author=Thavasu PW, Longhurst S, Joel SP, Slevin ML, Balkwill FR|title=Measuring cytokine levels in blood. Importance of anticoagulants, processing, and storage conditions. |journal=J Immunol Methods |year=1992 |volume=153 |issue=1\u20132 |pages=115\u201324 |pmid=1381403 |doi=10.1016/0022-1759(92)90313-i }}</ref>\n\nSerum is an essential factor for the self-renewal of [[embryonic stem cells]] in combination with the cytokine [[leukemia inhibitory factor]].{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Clinical and laboratory uses ==\nThe serum of [[convalescence|convalescent]] patients successfully recovering (or already recovered) from an [[infectious disease]] can be used as a [[biopharmaceutical]] in the treatment of other people with that disease, because the [[antibody|antibodies]] generated by the successful recovery are potent fighters of the [[pathogen]]. Such ''convalescent serum'' ([[antiserum]]) is a form of [[immunotherapy]].\n\nSerum is also used in [[Gel electrophoresis of proteins|protein electrophoresis]], due to the lack of [[fibrinogen]] which can cause false results. \n\n==Purification strategies==\nBlood serum and plasma are some of the largest sources of [[biomarker]]s, whether for diagnostics or therapeutics. Its vast dynamic range, further complicated by the presence of lipids, salts, and post-translational modifications, as well multiple mechanisms of degradation, presents challenges in analytical reproducibility, sensitivity, resolution, and potential efficacy. For analysis of biomarkers in blood serum samples, it is possible to do a pre-separation by [[free-flow electrophoresis]] that usually consists of a depletion of serum [[albumin]] protein.<ref name=\"Analysis of human plasma proteins: a focus on sample collection and separation using free-flow electrophoresis.\">Nissum M., Foucher AL.: ''Analysis of human plasma proteins: a focus on sample collection and separation using free-flow electrophoresis.'' In: ''Expert Rev Proteomics.'' Nr. 5, 2008, S. 571\u201387.</ref> This method enables greater penetration of the proteome via separation of a wide variety of charged or chargeable analytes, ranging from small molecules to cells.\n\n==Usage note==\nLike many other [[mass noun]]s, the word ''serum'' can be pluralized when used in certain [[word sense|senses]]. To speak of multiple serum specimens from multiple people (each with a unique population of antibodies), physicians sometimes speak of '''sera''' (the Latin plural, as opposed to ''serums'').\n\n== See also ==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Antiserum]]\n* [[Albumin]]\n* [[Blood fractionation]]\n* [[Globulin]]\n* [[Human serum albumin]]\n* [[Lipid]]\n* [[Serum iron]]\n* [[Serum protein electrophoresis]]\n* [[Serum-separating tube]]\n* [[Serum total protein]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |title=Concise Medical Dictionary |editor=Martin, Elizabeth A.|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location=[[Oxford, England]]|year=2007 |edition=7th|isbn=978-0-19-280697-0 |url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/views/ENTRY.html?subview=Main&entry=t60.e9203 |accessdate=8 September 2009}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia|author1=Wang, Wendy |author2=Srivastava, Sudhir |title=Serological Markers | encyclopedia=[[Encyclopedia of Public Health]]|editor=[[Lester Breslow]]|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers (United States)|Macmillan Reference USA]]|location=[[New York, New York]] |year=2002 |volume=4 |pages=1088\u20131090 }}\n{{refend}}\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wiktionary|serum|blood serum}}\n* [http://users.rcn.com/jkimball.ma.ultranet/BiologyPages/B/Blood.html Blood]\n\n{{blood tests}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Serology|*]]\n[[Category:Blood]]\n", "name_user": "Dfoxvog", "label": "safe", "comment": "warning about first paragraph no longer applies.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serum_(blood)"}
{"title_page": "Lila Lamgade", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Lila Lamgade\n| image          = Lila Lamgade.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Lila Lamgade\n| birth_date     = \n| birth_place    = \n|url=\n| position       = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| height         = \n| years1         = \n| clubs1         = \n| caps1          = \n| goals1         = \n| years2         = \n| clubs2         = \n| caps2          = \n| goals2         = \n| nationalyears1 = 2012\n| nationalteam1  = \n| nationalcaps1  = ?\n| nationalgoals1 = ?\n| nationalyears2 = 2012\u2014\n| nationalteam2  = [[Nepal women's national football team|Nepal]]\n| nationalcaps2  = \n| nationalgoals2 = \n}}\n'''Lila Lamgade''' (Nepali:\u0932\u093f\u0932\u093e \u0932\u093e\u092e\u094d\u0917\u093e\u0926\u0947) (born 1991 in [[Morang District|Morang]]){{citation needed|date=January 2018}} is a Nepalese women footballer who plays for the [[Nepal Army Club]], the [[Nepal women's national football team]].\n\n<ref>[http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-01-04/nepal-womens-national-football-team-to-participate-in-sag-2016-declared.html \"Nepal women's national football team to participate in SAG 2016 declared\"], ''The Kathmandu Post'', 4 January 2016</ref>She represented Nepal at the 2012 SAFF Women's Championship ,playing in the final against India.It was her international debute.\n\nShe received the best keeper award at women\u2019s national league 2016.\n\nShe had recently won the title of Best goalkeeper award at ANFA Women's league held on palpa and shyngja on 2017 where she played from the Taplejung district.Taplejung also dominated the individual award winning four of the five titles. Lila Lamgade was named the best goalkeeper.\n\n<ref>[https://thehimalayantimes.com/sports/taplejung-defeat-rautahat-anfa-women-football-tournament/]\n\n<ref>[http://admin.myrepublica.com/sports/story/41531/army-s-defeat-leaves-race-open-for-police-apf.html \"Army's defeat leaves race open for Police, APF\"], ''Republica'', 1 May 2016</ref> \n\n==Best Keeper Awards ==\n* Women\u2019s national league 2016<ref>[https://thehimalayantimes.com/sports/npc-edge-past-eastern-retain-league-title/ \"NPC edge past Eastern, retain league title\"], ''The Himalayan'', 3 May 2016</ref>\n* Women's League 2014\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamgade, Lila}}\n[[Category:Nepalese women's footballers]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Morang District]]\n[[Category:Women's association football goalkeepers]]\n\n\n{{Nepal-women-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Lila Lamgade\n| image          = Lila Lamgade.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = Lila Lamgade\n| birth_date     = \n| birth_place    = \n|url=\n| position       = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| height         = \n| years1         = \n| clubs1         = \n| caps1          = \n| goals1         = \n| years2         = \n| clubs2         = \n| caps2          = \n| goals2         = \n| nationalyears1 = 2012\n| nationalteam1  = \n| nationalcaps1  = ?\n| nationalgoals1 = ?\n| nationalyears2 = 2012\u2014\n| nationalteam2  = [[Nepal women's national football team|Nepal]]\n| nationalcaps2  = \n| nationalgoals2 = \n}}\n'''Lila Lamgade''' (Nepali:\u0932\u093f\u0932\u093e \u0932\u093e\u092e\u094d\u0917\u093e\u0926\u0947) (born 1991 in [[Morang District|Morang]]){{citation needed|date=January 2018}} is a Nepalese women footballer who plays for the [[Nepal Army Club]],\nShe represented Nepal at the 2012 SAFF Women's Championship ,playing in the final against India.It was her international debute.\n\nShe received the best keeper award at women\u2019s national league 2016.\n\nShe had recently won the title of Best goalkeeper award at ANFA Women's league held on palpa and shyngja on 2017 where she played from the Taplejung district.Taplejung also dominated the individual award winning four of the five titles. Lila Lamgade was named the best goalkeeper.<ref>[\nhttps://thehimalayantimes.com/sports/taplejung-defeat-rautahat-anfa-women-football-tournament/>\n<ref>[http://admin.myrepublica.com/sports/story/41531/army-s-defeat-leaves-race-open-for-police-apf.html \"Army's defeat leaves race open for Police, APF\"], ''Republica'', 1 May 2016</ref> and the [[Nepal women's national football team]].<ref>[http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-01-04/nepal-womens-national-football-team-to-participate-in-sag-2016-declared.html \"Nepal women's national football team to participate in SAG 2016 declared\"], ''The Kathmandu Post'', 4 January 2016</ref>\n\n==Best Keeper Awards ==\n* Women\u2019s national league 2016<ref>[https://thehimalayantimes.com/sports/npc-edge-past-eastern-retain-league-title/ \"NPC edge past Eastern, retain league title\"], ''The Himalayan'', 3 May 2016</ref>\n* Women's League 2014\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lamgade, Lila}}\n[[Category:Nepalese women's footballers]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Morang District]]\n[[Category:Women's association football goalkeepers]]\n\n\n{{Nepal-women-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Asmita Koirala", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lila_Lamgade"}
{"title_page": "Heosphora ablepta", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| taxon = Heosphora ablepta\n| authority = [[Alfred Jefferis Turner|Turner]], 1913\n| synonyms = ''Anerastria ablepta'' <small>[[Alfred Jefferis Turner|Turner]], 1913</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Heosphora ablepta''''' is a species of [[moth]] in the family [[Pyralidae]]. The species was first described by [[Alfred Jefferis Turner|Turner]] in 1913.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bie.ala.org.au/species/urn:lsid:biodiversity.org.au:afd.taxon:a47a0faa-fe33-4e67-8839-57a8bcf19c80|title=Heosphora ablepta (Turner, 1913)|website=Atlas of Living Australia|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhm.ac.uk/our-science/data/lepindex/detail/?taxonno=8952&page_no=1&page_size=30|title=LepIndex - ablepta|website=www.nhm.ac.uk|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biolib.cz/en/taxon/id1101606/|title= Heosphora ablepta (Turner, 1913) |website=www.biolib.cz|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n\n{{Pyralidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = \n| taxon = Heosphora ablepta\n| authority = [[Alfred Jefferis Turner|Turner]], 1913\n| synonyms = ''Anerastria ablepta'' <small>[[Alfred Jefferis Turner|Turner]], 1913</small>\n}}\n\n'''''Heosphora ablepta''''' is a species of [[moth]] in the family [[Pyralidae]]. The species was first described by [[Alfred Jefferis Turner|Turner]] in 1913.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bie.ala.org.au/species/urn:lsid:biodiversity.org.au:afd.taxon:a47a0faa-fe33-4e67-8839-57a8bcf19c80|title=Heosphora ablepta (Turner, 1913)|website=Atlas of Living Australia|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhm.ac.uk/our-science/data/lepindex/detail/?taxonno=8952&page_no=1&page_size=30|title=LepIndex - ablepta|website=www.nhm.ac.uk|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biolib.cz/en/taxon/id1101606/|title= Heosphora ablepta (Turner, 1913) |website=www.biolib.cz|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n", "name_user": "Elmidae", "label": "safe", "comment": "+{{Pyralidae-stub}} usingStubSorter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heosphora_ablepta"}
{"title_page": "Gje", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=February 2007}}\n{{For|the European wine classification organisation|Grand Jury Europ\u00e9en}}\n{{Cyrillic alphabet navbox\n|Heading=Cyrillic letter Gje\n|Image=Cyrillic letter Gje - uppercase and lowercase.svg\n|size=100px\n|uuc=0403\n|ulc=0453\n|sound = {{IPA|[\u025f]}}, {{IPA|[d\u0291]}}\n}}\n'''Gje''' (\u0403&nbsp;\u0453; italics: <span style=\"font-family: times, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-size: larger\">''\u0403''&nbsp;''\u0453''</span>) is a letter of the [[Cyrillic script]].\n\n\u0403 is used in [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]] to represent the [[voiced palatal plosive]] {{IPA|/\u025f/}}.\n\n\u0403 is most commonly romanized using the Latin letter G with [[Acute accent|acute]] {{angbr|\u01f5}}. When the [[Socialist Republic of Macedonia]] was part of [[SFR Yugoslavia]], the Macedonian '''\u0453''' was also transliterated as '''\u0111''' or '''dj'''.\n\nWords with this letter are often cognate with {{lang|bg|\u0436\u0434}} - ''zhd'' in [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] and  [[Dje]] (\u0402&nbsp;\u0452) in [[Serbian language|Serbian]]. For example, the Macedonian word for ''birth'' ({{lang|mk|\u0440\u0430\u0453\u0430\u045a\u0435}} is ''ra\u01f5anje'', which in Bulgarian is {{lang|bg|\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0435}} - ''razhdane'', and in Serbian {{lang|sr|\u0440\u0430\u0452\u0430\u045a\u0435}} - ''ra\u0111anje'').\n\n==Related letters and other similar characters==\n*\u0413 \u0433: [[Ge (Cyrillic)|Cyrillic letter Ge]]\n*\u0402 \u0452: [[Dje|Cyrillic letter Dje]]\n*\u040c \u045c: [[Kje|Cyrillic letter Kje]]\n\n{{anchor|Encodings}}\n\n==Computing codes==\n\n{{charmap\n|0403|name1=Cyrillic Capital Letter Gje\n|0453|name2=Cyrillic Small Letter Gje\n|map1=[[Code page 855]] |map1char1=83 |map1char2=82\n|map2=[[Windows-1251]] |map2char1=81 |map2char2=83\n|map3=[[ISO-8859-5]] |map3char1=A3 |map3char2=F3\n|map4=[[Macintosh Cyrillic encoding|Macintosh Cyrillic]] |map4char1=AE |map4char2=AF\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|\u0403}}\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|\u0453}}\n\n\n{{Cyrillic-alphabet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=February 2007}}\n{{For|the European wine classification organisation|Grand Jury Europ\u00e9en}}\n{{Cyrillic alphabet navbox\n|Heading=Cyrillic letter Gje\n|Image=Cyrillic letter Gje - uppercase and lowercase.svg\n|size=100px\n|uuc=0403\n|ulc=0453\n|sound = {{IPA|[\u025f]}}, {{IPA|[d\u0291]}}\n}}\n'''Gje''' (\u0403&nbsp;\u0453; italics: <span style=\"font-family: times, 'Times New Roman', serif; font-size: larger\">''\u0403''&nbsp;''\u0453''</span>) is a letter of the [[Cyrillic script]].\n\n\u0403 is used in [[Macedonian language|Macedonian]] to represent the [[voiced palatal plosive]] {{IPA|/\u025f/}}.\n\n\u0403 is most commonly romanized using the Latin letter G with [[Acute accent|acute]] {{angbr|\u01f5}}. When the [[Socialist Republic of Macedonia]] was part of [[SFR Yugoslavia]], the Macedonian '''\u0453''' was also transliterated as '''\u0111''' or '''dj'''.\n\nWords with this letter are often cognate with {{lang|bg|\u0436\u0434}} - ''zhd'' in [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] and  [[Dje]] (\u0402&nbsp;\u0452) in [[Serbo-Croatian]]. For example, the Macedonian word for ''birth'' ({{lang|mk|\u0440\u0430\u0453\u0430\u045a\u0435}} is ''ra\u01f5anje'', which in Bulgarian is {{lang|bg|\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0435}} - ''razhdane'', and in Serbian {{lang|sr|\u0440\u0430\u0452\u0430\u045a\u0435}} - ''ra\u0111anje'').\n\n==Related letters and other similar characters==\n*\u0413 \u0433: [[Ge (Cyrillic)|Cyrillic letter Ge]]\n*\u0402 \u0452: [[Dje|Cyrillic letter Dje]]\n*\u040c \u045c: [[Kje|Cyrillic letter Kje]]\n\n{{anchor|Encodings}}\n\n==Computing codes==\n\n{{charmap\n|0403|name1=Cyrillic Capital Letter Gje\n|0453|name2=Cyrillic Small Letter Gje\n|map1=[[Code page 855]] |map1char1=83 |map1char2=82\n|map2=[[Windows-1251]] |map2char1=81 |map2char2=83\n|map3=[[ISO-8859-5]] |map3char1=A3 |map3char2=F3\n|map4=[[Macintosh Cyrillic encoding|Macintosh Cyrillic]] |map4char1=AE |map4char2=AF\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|\u0403}}\n*{{Wiktionary-inline|\u0453}}\n\n\n{{Cyrillic-alphabet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "SrpskiAnonimac", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gje"}
